<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900608-0069</DOCNO><DOCID>900608-0069.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Nevada Power Co.:   About 900 Workers Strike,   Affecting Entire Operation</HL><DATE>06/08/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   NVP LABOR</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><LP>   Nevada Power Co., Las Vegas, Nev., said about 900 clericaland plant workers went out on strike, affecting the company'sentire operation.   The company said it believed it could provide service forits 328,000 existing customers by using supervisory andsalaried personnel. But new construction for residential andbusiness connections will be delayed or suspended, thecompany said.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;That's where the crunch is going to come,&quot; said DavidBarneby, vice president for power supply. &quot;We're in the midstof a huge building boom here.&quot;   The union local's business manager, Jim Brimer, disagreed.&quot;There will be tremendous delays in restoring service ifthere are any power outtages,&quot; he said. Las Vegas hasexperienced 100-degree heat all week. On Wednesday, membersof the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workersoverwhelmingly rejected a tentative four-year contract. Thecompany rejected a new union proposal yesterday, promptingthe walkout. The major issues are wages, medical benefits andovertime.</TEXT></DOC>